---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { site } from "../data/site";

const researchThreads = [
  {
    id: "measurement",
    title: "Measurement Before Modeling",
    body:
      "A lot of empirical work fails before the model starts, because the measure is doing too much quiet work. I study how to define and validate measures for open-ended survey answers, legislative text, state capacity, public opinion, and other concepts that do not arrive as clean variables."
  },
  {
    id: "text",
    title: "Text as Institutional Evidence",
    body:
      "Text is not just a bag of words in my work. Bill sections, committee hearings, agency language, and country statements are records of institutional behavior. The point of the NLP is to recover something substantively meaningful from those records."
  },
  {
    id: "design",
    title: "Design Under Real Constraints",
    body:
      "Policy and program evaluations rarely get the clean assignment mechanism we would like. I work on designs that make the identifying assumptions visible, especially when treatment timing, administrative records, and implementation quality are part of the problem."
  },
  {
    id: "public-opinion",
    title: "Public Opinion After Conversation",
    body:
      "The deliberation work asks whether structured discussion does more than move survey marginals for a weekend. The stronger test is whether people leave with different knowledge, reasoning, attention, and later political behavior."
  }
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title={`Research | ${site.name}`}
  description="Research on measurement, text, causal inference, institutions, and public opinion."
>
  <section class="panel span-12">
    <div class="eyebrow">Research</div>
    <h1>Research</h1>
    <p class="lede section-intro">
      I work on measurement problems that sit between method and substance. The questions are
      political and social; the evidence is often textual, administrative, behavioral, or
      otherwise awkward.
    </p>
    <p class="section-intro">
      That awkwardness is the point. If the construct were obvious and the data were clean, the
      methods would matter less.
    </p>
    <div class="anchor-row">
      {researchThreads.map((thread) => (
        <a class="anchor-link" href={`#${thread.id}`}>{thread.title}</a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-grid">
    {researchThreads.map((thread) => (
      <article class="panel span-6 theme-card" id={thread.id}>
        <div>
          <h2>{thread.title}</h2>
          <p>{thread.body}</p>
        </div>
      </article>
    ))}
  </section>

  <section class="section-grid">
    <div class="panel span-8">
      <h2>How I Use Methods</h2>
      <p>
        I am not especially interested in using a method because it is fashionable. I am interested
        in whether it helps answer a question that would otherwise be measured badly, inferred too
        confidently, or left vague.
      </p>
      <p>
        That is why the same site has papers on LLMs and legislative complexity, malpractice claims,
        state capacity, congressional agenda control, automated deliberation, and survey
        nonresponse. They look different from the outside. They share a worry about whether the
        quantity being analyzed is the quantity the argument needs.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="panel span-4">
      <h2>Where to Go Next</h2>
      <div class="compact-list">
        <div class="compact-item">
          <p><a href="/publications">Read paper summaries and working papers</a></p>
        </div>
        <div class="compact-item">
          <p><a href="/talks">See recent talks and short courses</a></p>
        </div>
        <div class="compact-item">
          <p><a href="/cv">Download the current CV</a></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
